## Page 31

Gaining Bonds
During character creation, characters are encouraged
to take a Bond or two. During the course of the game,
the GM may prompt you to clear existing Bonds if they
are resolved, or add new Bonds that arise throughout
the course of the campaign.
Example:
GM: You see the symbol of the Black Heart Cabal on the
corpse. It is unmistakable. How do you react?
Erriana: I .place my hand on my heart and say “It’s a
matter of honour. I’ll let no member of the Black Heart
Cabal live.”
GM: Okay. Mark down a new Bond: Vendetta against
the Black Heart Cabal.
Exploiting Bonds
If your character is in a situation where your Bonds
will inconvenience, harm, or otherwise make the
situation worse, someone, including you, can Exploit
your Bond by describing how its relevant and offering
a complication. In that case, you get two options:
Bonds
• Accept the complication and gain +1 Luck Point
Bonds are short phrases that describe something unique about • Spend a Luck to avoid the complication
your character personality. They are not necessary something
that makes you a “bad person”, but something that can compli- Example:
cate your character’s life. Whether its a vendetta, a personality
compulsion, a large debt, an inconvenient loyalty, or a forbidden GM: An old Cyrodiilic man shakes your hand and tells
love, Bonds should be thematic and resonate with your character you that adventurers are rare these days, and is willing
to bring depth and more importantly, interesting and organic to help you. “The name is Celvus, by the way. I’m the
plot hooks. head of this village,” he says in a friendly tone. Roll
Observe for me.
Example Bonds include:
• I’ve experienced great loss which I fill by obtaining material Erriana: I pass.
goods, whatever the cost.
• At the slightest insult to my honor, I find it difficult to GM: While shaking his hand, you notice a tattoo. The
temper my anger. mark of the Black Heart Cabal.
